                <div class="css-9ul5p9">
                 <p class="comment__09f24__D0cxf css-qgunke">
                  <span class="raw__09f24__T4Ezm" lang="en">
                   We landed in Fresno and we were hungry for some food. Knowing we were in California, we thought tacos would be a safe bet to find something really delicious. Using Yelp, we came across El Toro tortillería. These were THE BEST tortillas I've ever had. The fillings for the tacos were flavorful and amazing as well. If you like tamales, you also have to try that.
                   <br/>
                   <br/>
                   It's a plus if you speak Spanish, but appreciation of good food is the same in every language. There's a couple of places to sit and eat, but we saw most people taking takeout.
                   <br/>
                   <br/>
                   We rarely go back to the same place more than once when we're on vacation, but we both decided we were going back as soon as we walked out.
                  </span>
                 </p>

                  <span class="css-1oibaro" data-font-weight="semibold">
                   <a class="css-19v1rkv" href="/biz_photos/el-toro-tortilleria-fresno?userid=lPNsKsD-HvdgkzfGq-Gjig">
                    7 photos
                   </a>
                  </span>

                </div>
                <div class="css-9ul5p9">
                 <p class="comment__09f24__D0cxf css-qgunke">
                  <span class="raw__09f24__T4Ezm" lang="en">
                   An El Toro Taqueria and Carniceria in Fresno? My prayers have been answered! Known for its variety of delicious Mexican meats, including slow-cooked carnitas, and tortillas that are freshly made in-house. As a long-time Orange County resident, I used to frequent the sister markets and butcher shops in Santa Ana. It has been nearly two years since I moved to Fresno County and trying to find a really good taqueria has been mostly a disappointing experience for the man still known to some as the Taco King. So never in my wildest dreams could I have imagined a sister shop in the Central Valley, let alone a mere 15 to 20-minute drive from Northeast Clovis where I live.
                   <br/>
                   <br/>
                   Now, they call it something slightly different here but I was able to confirm with the manager that they are one and the same as the carnicerias in Orange County that bear the name El Toro.
                   <br/>
                   <br/>
                   Many carnicerias like this one prepares a good variety of cooked meats, including hard-to-find choices which include the following: chicharrón (deep fried pig skin), cabeza de res (beef head), tripa (tripe), buche (pork stomach lining), birria de res (beef stew), birria de res (goat stew), along with more familiar choices like asada (beef), pollo (chicken) and carnitas (braised pork). They spare no parts of the animal so be open to being more adventurous when you order from here. Ojo (eyeball) anyone?
                   <br/>
                   <br/>
                   Combination plates with rice and refried beans, tacos, burritos, and tostadas can be prepared with any of the meat choices. The serving sizes are very generous and the prices are reasonable. Mariscos (seafood), salsas, cheeses, freshly made tortilla chips, and aqua frescas (sweetened fruit waters) are also sold here.
                  </span>
                 </p>
                </div>
                <div class="css-1cfy6na">
                 <div class="arrange__09f24__LDfbs gutter-2__09f24__CCmUo layout-wrap__09f24__GEBlv css-na7xnn">
                  <div class="arrange-unit__09f24__rqHTg css-1qn0b6x">
                   <div class="photo-container-small__09f24__pQ5jg css-1qn0b6x">

                 <p class="comment__09f24__D0cxf css-qgunke">
                  <span class="raw__09f24__T4Ezm" lang="en">
                   Here at El Toro Tortilleria food is good, friendly service  The price is fair, but quality control is "no bueno." We stopped by to get something to eat today, and as I was eating these chicken tamales, I got this long piece of kinda brownish red long hair in my mouth, which is not part of the fiber from anything; it's actually a long reddish brown hair. Please step up your quality control and put on a hat or hair nets on if possible.
                   <br/>
                   <br/>
                   Update: The owner responded to my comments immediately, and I decided to revise my review. I know in the food industry, it's hard to make sure everything goes right. The way David, the owner, replied, he didn't start an argument or escalate further, which I truly appreciate for good customer service. If you got good service, good food, and a fair price, you shouldn't have to worry about a bad or negative Yelp review. For a fact i've know several business who has bad and negative reviews and they're still thriving and they don't even respond to the Yelps review.  Thank you, David, and your friendly employees take care.
                  </span>

                  <div class="arrange-unit__09f24__rqHTg arrange-unit-fill__09f24__CUubG css-1qn0b6x">
                   <span class="css-chan6m">
                    Feb 14, 2023
                   </span>
                  </div>
                 </div>
                </div>
                <div class="css-9ul5p9">
                 <p class="comment__09f24__D0cxf css-qgunke">
                  <span class="raw__09f24__T4Ezm" lang="en">
                   Came here in a whim on a Saturday to try it out. The fresh tortillas are delicious, of course like most would be hot off the press. It's literally a tortilla factory and they make and serve hot food to order.
                   <br/>
                   <br/>
                   We ordered a Gordita with all the toppings (lettuce, tomato, cheese, sour cream), one cabeza and one tripa taco, a carnitas regular burrito (there's also a 'super' burrito), and a pork tamale.
                   <br/>
                   <br/>
                   The Gordita was cold by the time we got to it but the chicharron inside was delicious. It would've been perfect if it was warm, next time we probably won't get the toppings so we can pop it in the toaster oven before we eat it.
                   <br/>
                   <br/>
                   The tacos were good, cabeza was flavorful and soft. The tripas was soft, just a heads up if you prefer crispy; not sure if they'd be willing to make them crispy or not but they still tasted good.
                   <br/>
                   <br/>
                   The carnitas burrito was excellent. The meat was so flavorful and tender; I think next time I'd love to get just a carnitas plate/combo. The beans and rice in the burrito was also very good, and the proportions were just right.
                   <br/>
                   <br/>
                   The tamale was good too. The masa had good flavor but the texture was a little spongy which I personally didn't mind. The pork inside also had a lot of flavor and was cooked really well.
                   <br/>
                   <br/>
                   Will definitely be coming back to try more. They had great options for catering and I would really love to take advantage of their catering for an event. All of this food plus a a package of 30 tortillas was less than $30 - so worth it.
                  </span>
                 </p>
                </div>

                <div class="css-9ul5p9">
                 <p class="comment__09f24__D0cxf css-qgunke">
                  <span class="raw__09f24__T4Ezm" lang="en">
                   WOW. I really hesitate to say this is the best carne asada taco I've ever had, but I'm just going to flat out say it - BEST CARNE ASADA TACO.  I dare you to try it and tell me otherwise.
                   <br/>
                   <br/>
                   First, they make their own incredibly warm, fluffy, flaky, corn tortillas. I mean, top notch. But the true winner is the meat. I personally am not a fan of carne asada because it can get dry and chewy.  This places serves up super juicy and tender meat. And the portion size is perfect. Topped with diced onions and cilantro, it was just the perfect taco. The juices come flowing out, and salsa isn't even needed. Still, I couldn't help but add a touch of verde salsa.
                   <br/>
                   <br/>
                   I also purchased a small horchata and it was also delicious. I bought a few Rajas con Queso tamales that I'm saving for later.
                  </span>
                 </p>

Carniceria in Fresno? My prayers have been answered! Known for its variety of delicious Mexican meats, including slow-cooked carnitas, and tortillas that are freshly made in-house. As a long-time Orange County resident, I used to frequent the sister markets and butcher shops in Santa Ana. It has been nearly two years since I moved to Fresno County and trying to find a really good taqueria has been mostly a disappointing experience for the man still known to some as the Taco King. So never in my wildest dreams could I have imagined a sister shop in the Central Valley, let alone a mere 15 to 20-minute drive from Northeast Clovis where I live.<br&gt;<br&gt;Now, they call it something slightly different here but I was able to confirm with the manager that they are one and the same as the carnicerias in Orange County that bear the name El Toro. <br&gt;<br&gt;Many carnicerias like this one prepares a good variety of cooked meats, including hard-to-find choices which include the following: chicharrón (deep fried pig skin), cabeza de res (beef head), tripa (tripe), buche (pork stomach lining), birria de res (beef stew), birria de res (goat stew), along with more familiar choices like asada (beef), pollo (chicken) and carnitas (braised pork). They spare no parts of the animal so be open to being more adventurous when you order from here. Ojo (eyeball) anyone?<br&gt;<br&gt;Combination plates with rice and refried beans, tacos, burritos, and tostadas can be prepared with any of the meat choices. The serving sizes are very generous and the prices are reasonable. El Toro Taqueria and Carniceria in Fresno? My prayers have been answered! Known for its variety of delicious Mexican meats, including slow-cooked carnitas, and tortillas that are freshly made in-house. As a long-time Orange County resident, I used to frequent the sister markets and butcher shops in Santa Ana. It has been nearly two years since I moved to Fresno County and trying to find a really good taqueria has been mostly a disappointing experience for the man still known to some as the Taco King. So never in my wildest dreams could I have imagined a sister shop in the Central Valley, let alone a mere 15 to 20-minute drive from Northeast Clovis where I live.\n\nNow, they call it something slightly different here but I was able to confirm with the manager that they are one and the same as the carnicerias in Orange County that bear the name El Toro. \n\nMany carnicerias like this one prepares a good variety of cooked meats, including hard-to-find choices which include the following: chicharrón (deep fried pig skin), cabeza de res (beef head), tripa (tripe), buche (pork stomach lining), birria de res (beef stew), birria de res (goat stew), along with more familiar choices like asada (beef), pollo (chicken) and carnitas (braised pork). They spare no parts of the animal so be open to being more adventurous when you order from here. Ojo (eyeball) anyone?\n\nCombination plates with rice and refried beans, tacos, burritos, and tostadas can be prepared with any of the meat choices. The serving sizes are very generous and the prices are reasonable. Mariscos (seafood), salsas, cheeses, freshly made tortilla chips, and aqua frescas (sweetened fruit waters) are also sold El Toro Taqueria and Carniceria in Fresno? My prayers have been answered! Known for its variety of delicious Mexican meats, including slow-cooked carnitas, and tortillas that are freshly made in-house. As a long-time Orange County resident, I used to frequent the sister markets and butcher shops in Santa Ana. It has been nearly two years since I moved to Fresno County and trying to find a really good taqueria has been mostly a disappointing experience for the man still known to some as the Taco King. So never in my wildest dreams could I have imagined a sister shop in the Central Valley, let alone a mere 15 to 20-minute drive from Northeast Clovis where I live.\n\nNow, they call it something slightly different here but I was able to confirm with the manager that they are one and the same as the carnicerias in Orange County that bear the name El Toro. \n\nMany carnicerias like this one prepares a good variety of cooked meats, including hard-to-find choices which include the following: chicharrón (deep fried pig skin), cabeza de res (beef head), tripa (tripe), buche (pork stomach lining), birria de res (beef stew), birria de res (goat stew), along with more familiar choices like asada (beef), pollo (chicken) and carnitas (braised pork). They spare no parts of the animal so be open to being more adventurous when you order from here. Ojo (eyeball) anyone?\n\nCombination plates with rice and refried beans, tacos, burritos, and tostadas can be prepared with any of the meat choices. The serving sizes are very generous and the prices are reasonable. Mariscos (seafood), salsas, cheeses, freshly made tortilla chips, and aqua frescas (sweetened fruit waters) are also sold The masa had good flavor but the texture was a little spongy which I personally didn&#x27;t mind. They had great options for catering and I would really love to take advantage of their catering for an event.
